message.content:
The command is trying to use the key file "UserKey.pem" located in the user's home directory, but it doesn't have permission to access it. 


To fix this, you need to make sure that the key file has read permissions for the user running the command. You can check the current permissions using:


```bash
ls -l ~/UserKey.pem
```

If it shows something like `-rw-------` or `-r--------`, then only the owner of the file (you) has read permission, and other users cannot access it. To change this, you can run:

	
```bash
chmod 400 ~/UserKey.pem
```

This will give read-only permissions for the owner of the file (you) and no permission to others. If it's still not working, you may need to change the ownership of the file using:


```bash	
chown <username> ~/UserKey.pem
```

Replace `<username>` with your username. After this, try running the `ssh` command again.
